    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="466"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d466">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_CFM1">CFM</gloss> files, lot M 88, box 169, “<persName
                        corresp="#p_CHURCHILLWS1">Churchill</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_EDENA1"
                        >Eden</persName> Visit”</note>
                <head>No. 466<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of a Meeting of Secretary of State <persName
                            corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> and Foreign Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d466fn1">Drafted on June 27. According to the notation on
                        the source text this meeting took place at the White House at noon on June
                        26; however, the schedule of meetings indicates that on June 26 <persName
                            corresp="#p_DULLESJF1">Dulles</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> were meeting at the Department of
                        State at noon. Presumably then, this meeting took place on June 25,
                        immediately before that described in CEV <gloss target="#t_MC1"
                        >MC</gloss>–2, <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>CEV <gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>–1</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-25">June 25, 1954</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>Participants:</head>
                    <item>
                        <list type="simple">
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                            </head>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <list type="simple">
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">United Kingdom</hi>
                            </head>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Anthony Eden</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_CACCIASHA1">Sir Harold Caccia</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>
                                <persName>Christopher Soames</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Germany and <gloss target="#t_EDC1">E.D.C.</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>At noon today while waiting to join the President and Prime Minister, there was a
                    considerable discussion of the problem of Germany. The Secretary and Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> agreed that their estimates
                    coincided on the importance of taking positive action in support of <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName> if the French Assembly recessed
                    this summer without ratifying <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>. They were in
                    general agreement that a way should be found to separate the contractuals from
                    the <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>, without prejudice to possible later
                    action by the French Assembly in approving <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>
                    in the fall. This would require some undertaking from <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1">Adenauer</persName>
                    <pb facs="1125" n="1077" xml:id="pg_1077"/> that Germany would not unilaterally
                    rearm during the period in which the fate of <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss>
                    would be settled. The Secretary explained the constitutional requirements with
                    which we were faced in connection with modifying the Bonn Treaty so as to remove
                    the link with the <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss> Treaty.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d466fn2">For the text of the Convention on Relations Between the
                        Three Powers and the Federal Republic of Germany (the Bonn Treaty), signed
                        at Bonn on May 26, 1952, see <ref target="frus1952-54v07p1#pg_112">vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vii</hi>, Part 1, p. 112</ref>; for the text of the
                            <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss> Treaty, signed at Paris on May 27,
                        1952, see <hi rend="italic">Documents</hi> (R.I.I.A.) for 1952, pp.
                        116–162.</note> Mr. <persName corresp="#p_EDENA1">Eden</persName> was
                    obviously unaware of this complication but recognized it when it was pointed
                    out. There was agreement that <persName corresp="#p_ADENAUERK1"
                        >Adenauer</persName> should be consulted before any approach to the
                    French.</p>
            </div>
